aphics2_title1 = \n| demographics2_info1 = \n| timezone1 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset1 = -5\n| timezone1_DST = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = -4\n| timezone2 = \n| utc_offset2 = \n| timezone2_DST = \n| utc_offset2_DST = \n| postal_code_type = [[ZIP code]]\n| postal_code = 18015\n| postal2_code_type = \n| postal2_code = \n| area_code_type = \n| area_code = [[Area codes 610 and 484|610 and 484]]\n| geocode = \n| iso_code = \n| blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n| blank_info = 42-27008\n| blank1_name = \n| blank1_info = \n| blank2_name = \n| blank2_info = \n| blank_name_sec2 = \n| blank_info_sec2 = \n| blank1_name_sec2 = \n| blank1_info_sec2 = \n| blank2_name_sec2 = Wikimedia Commons\n| blank2_info_sec2 = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.fountainhill.org}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Fountain Hill''' is a borough in [[Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Lehigh County]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States.  It is a suburb of [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania]] in the [[Lehigh Valley]] region of the state. Fountain Hill is included in the [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]]-[[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]]-[[Easton, Pennsylvania|Easton]], PA-[[New Jersey|NJ]] [[Lehigh Valley|Metropolitan Statistical Area]], which is also included in the [[New York City]]-[[Newark, New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|NY]]-[[New Jersey|NJ]]-[[Connecticut|CT]]-PA [[New York metropolitan area|Combined Statistical Area]].\n\nThe population of Fountain Hill was 4,597 at the 2010 census.\n\n==Geography==\nFountain Hill is located at {{Coord|40|36|6|N|75|23|47|W|type:city}} (40.601698, -75.396357).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the borough has a total area of {{convert|0.7|sqmi|km2}}, of which, {{convert|0.7|sqmi|km2}} of it is land and 1.41% is water. The Borough is approximately {{convert|450|acre|km2}}, predominantly residential in character, with approximately 1,754 dwelling units. It uses the Bethlehem [[ZIP code]] of 18015. [https://web.archive.org/web/20120324210531/http://www.hipcodes.com/18015/]\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 1214\n|1910= 1388\n|1920= 2339\n|1930= 4568\n|1940= 4804\n|1950= 5456\n|1960= 5428\n|1970= 5384\n|1980= 4805\n|1990= 4637\n|2000= 4614\n|2010= 4597\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=4715\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=Sources:<ref name=\"USDecennialCensus\">{{cite web|title=Census of Population and Housing|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref><ref name=CensusPopEst>{{cite web|title=Incorporated Places and Minor Civil Divisions Datasets: Subcounty Resident Population Estimates: April 1, 2010 to July 1, 2012|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|work=Population Estimates|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=11 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611010502/http://www.census.gov/popest/data/cities/totals/2012/SUB-EST2012.html|archivedate=11 June 2013}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2010, there were 4,597 people living in the borough.  The racial makeup of the borough was 81.4% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 6.6% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.1% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.8% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.0% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 7.7% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 3.4% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 22.5% of the population.\n\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 4,614 people, 1,911 households, and 1,125 families living in the borough. The [[population density]] was 6,542.8 people per square mile (2,509.1/km\u00b2). There were 2,029 housing units at an average density of 2,877.2 per square mile (1,103.4/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the borough was 86.84% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 3.81% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.20% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.91% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 6.00% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.23% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 10.73% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,911 households, out of which 26.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 43.8% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 11.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 41.1% were non-families. 35.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.28 and the average family size was 2.99.\n\nIn the borough the population was spread out, with 21.7% under the age of 18, 7.3% from 18 to 24, 29.0% from 25 to 44, 21.0% from 45 to 64, and 21.0% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 40 years. For every 100 females there were 84.0 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 78.9 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the borough was $40,318, and the median income for a family was $46,336. Males had a median income of $34,808 versus $26,537 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the borough was $18,508. About 7.5% of families and 8.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 13.1% of those under age 18 and 5.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\nThe Borough is served by the [[Bethlehem Area School District]]. John Spirk Elementary, also known as Fountain Hill Elementary School, is the neighborhood public school in the Borough.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from the Lehigh Valley}}\n*[[Stephen Vincent Ben\u00e9t]], author\n*[[Joseph F. Brennan]], State Representative, 133rd district (Ret.)\n* [[Edwin Drake]], discoverer of crude oil in [[Titusville, Pennsylvania|Titusville PA]], lived and died in Fountain Hill\n*[[T. J. Rooney]], State Representative, 133rd district (Ret.)\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fountainhill.org/ Borough of Fountain Hill official website]\n\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n|Centre = Fountain Hill\n|North = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]]\n|Northeast = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]]\n|East = [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]]\n|Southeast = [[Lower Saucon Township, Northampton County, Pennsylvania|Lower Saucon Township]]\n|South = [[Center Valley, Pennsylvania|Center Valley]]\n|Southwest = [[Summit Lawn, Pennsylvania|Summit Lawn]] ; [[Salisbury Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Salisbury Township]]\n|West =  [[Allentown, Pennsylvania|Allentown]] ; [[Salisbury Township, Lehigh County, Pennsylvania|Salisbury Township]]\n|Northwest = \n|image =  \n}}\n\n{{commons category|Fountain Hill, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Lehigh Valley}}\n{{Lehigh County, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Pennsylvania}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1893]]\n[[Category:Boroughs in Lehigh County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fountain_Hill,_Pennsylvania"}
{"title_page": "2003\u201304 U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo season", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club season\n|club=[[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo]]\n|season=2003-04\n|manager=[[Silvio Baldini]]<ref>(Until round 24).</ref><br />[[Francesco Guidolin]]\n|chairman=[[Maurizio Zamparini]]\n|chrtitle=President\n|league=[[Serie B]]\n|league result=[[2003-04 Serie B|1\u00ba]] (promoted to [[2004-05 Serie A|Serie A]])\n|cup1=[[Coppa Italia]]\n|cup1 result=[[2003-04 Coppa Italia|Eightfinals]]\n|league topscorer=[[Luca Toni]] (30)\n|season topscorer=[[Luca Toni|Toni]] (30)\n|abbonati=12.771\n|spettatori max=\n|spettatori min=\n|spettatori media=\n|prevseason=[[2002\u201303 U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo season|2002-03]]\n|nextseason=[[2004\u201305 U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo season|2004-05]]\n}}\n\n'''[[U.S. Citt\u00e0 di Palermo]]''' played the '''season 2003-04''' in the [[Serie B]] league. The ''rosanero'' ended the season in first place, being crowned Serie B champions and promoted to [[Serie A]] after 31 years in the lower divisions.\n\n==Summary==\nAmbitious Palermo failed to gain promotion to [[Serie A]] in the previous season following a 3-0 away defeat in the final match against [[U.S. Lecce|Lecce]], which were promoted at Palermo's place<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080914131104/http://www.ilpalermocalcio.it/it/0304/numeri.jsp|title= Season 2002-30 Palermo |publisher=ilpalermocalcio.it|language=Italian}}</ref>. That dramatic defeat was also the last appearance in his playing career for team captain [[Antonino Asta]], who seriously injured during the match and did not manage to recover; he was part of the first team squad in the season 2003-04, without however making a single appearance. Following the events, Palermo made a number of prominent signings in the summer market, such as [[Eugenio Corini]], [[Andrea Gasbarroni]] and [[Luca Toni]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2004/giugno/13/ultima_notte_Toni_ga_10_0406135443.shtml|publisher=gazzetta.it|title= The last night of Toni|language=Italian}}</ref>; in addition, Palermo-born star [[Gaetano Vasari]] agreed to join the ''rosanero'' with a salary based on the number of appearances he would have made in the season. [[Silvio Baldini]] was appointed as new boss to replace [[Nedo Sonetti]]. Several football pundits suggested Palermo to be the real favourite team to win the Serie B league because of the quality of its roster.\n\nThe team made a very impressive start by defeating [[Gianfranco Zola]]'s [[Cagliari Calcio]], and managed to be always in the promotion spots. However, following a surprising 3-1 home defeat to [[Salernitana Calcio 1919|Salernitana]] that brought Palermo down to third place, Baldini heavily criticized club chairman [[Maurizio Zamparini]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071116150927/http://www.raisport.rai.it/pub/sezione/raiSportSezioneIndex/0%2C5785%2C_205_60_1416%2C00.html|title= Zamparini Interview|language=Italian|publisher=raisport.it}}</ref> who consequently fired him and appointed [[Francesco Guidolin]] at his place. On the last day of the January transfer market, three new notable signings were made: [[Antonio Filippini]], [[Emanuele Filippini]] and [[Fabio Grosso]]. Palermo later returned to top the table and eventually won the league, ending with the same points than Cagliari, but being crowned as Serie B champions due to head-to-head matches.\n\n==2003-04 squad==\n{{Efs start|[[Serie B 2003-04|Serie B]]|[[Coppa Italia 2003-04|Coppa Italia]]}}\n{{Efs player|no=1|nat=Italy|name=[[Gianluca Berti]]|pos=GK|42|-35|1|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=12|nat=Italy|name=[[Nicola Santoni]]|pos=GK|4|-4|4|-6}}\n{{Efs player|no=84|nat=Italy|name=[[Paolo Comi]]|pos=GK|0|0|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=4|nat=Italy|name=[[Gianluca Atzori]]|pos=DF|17|0|1|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=6|nat=Italy|name=[[Christian Terlizzi]]|pos=DF|12|0|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=13|nat=Italy|name=[[Pietro Accardi]]|pos=DF|32|0|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=18|nat=Italy|name=[[Fabio Grosso]]|pos=DF|21|1|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=21|nat=Italy|name=[[Giuseppe Biava]]|pos=DF|19|3|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=25|nat=Sierra Leone|name=[[Kewullay Conteh]]|pos=DF|32|0|2|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=29|nat=Romania|name=[[Valentin N\u0103stase]]|pos=DF|16|1|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=81|nat=Italy|name=[[Michele Ferri]]|pos=DF|36|1|3|1}}\n{{Efs player|no=5|nat=Italy|name=[[Eugenio Corini]]|pos=MF|40|12|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=7|nat=Italy|name=[[Gaetano Vasari]]|pos=MF|26|1|4|1}}\n{{Efs player|no=8|nat=Italy|name=[[Daniele Di Donato]]|pos=MF|39|3|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=10|nat=Italy|name=[[Lamberto Zauli]]|pos=MF|21|4|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=11|nat=Italy|name=[[Salvatore Masiello]]|pos=MF|18|0|4|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=17|nat=Italy|name=[[Antonino Asta]]|pos=MF|0|0|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=22|nat=Italy|name=[[Massimo Mutarelli]]|pos=MF|41|2|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=23|nat=Italy|name=[[Emanuele Filippini]]|pos=MF|20|4|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=26|nat=Italy|name=[[Antonio Filippini]]|pos=MF|21|2|0|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=46|nat=Italy|name=[[Andrea Gasbarroni]]|pos=MF|39|6|2|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=79|nat=Italy|name=[[Evans Soligo]]|pos=MF|9|0|4|1}}\n{{Efs player|no=82|nat=Italy|name=[[Nicola Milano]]|pos=MF|0|0|1|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=9|nat=Italy|name=[[Luca Toni]]|pos=FW|45|30|2|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=20|nat=Italy|name=[[Simone Pepe]]|pos=FW|19|1|5|2}}\n{{Efs player|no=24|nat=Nigeria|name=[[John Otuagomah Olufemi]]|pos=FW|0|0|1|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=30|nat=Brazil|name=[[Jedaias Capucho Neves|Jeda]]|pos=FW|17|3|0|0}}\n|-\n|colspan=\"10\"|''Players sold or loaned out during the January transfer market:''\n{{Efs player|no=3|nat=Italy|name=[[Francesco Modesto]]|pos=DF|1|0|5|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=18|nat=Italy|name=[[Franco Brienza]]|pos=MF|18|1|3|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=21|nat=Romania|name=[[Paul Codrea]]|pos=MF|8|0|4|0}}\n{{Efs player|no=23|nat=Italy|name=[[Ighli Vannucchi]]|pos=MF|8|0|3|2}}\n|}\n\n===January transfer market bids===\n;'''In'''\n{|\n{{Football squad player|no=18|nat=Italy|name=[[